# UI Debugging Rule (Prefer Agent Browser)

## Core Policy

- For UI/UX issues and investigations requiring on-screen reproduction, **always prioritize agent-browser**.
- Try agent-browser before other browser tools (MCP chrome-devtools, playwright).
- Work back and forth between the browser and source code, cycling quickly through **reproduce → hypothesize cause → fix → re-verify**.

## Advantages of agent-browser

| Feature | Description |
|------|------|
| **AI-optimized** | Use `snapshot -i -c` to obtain element references (`@e1`, `@e2`) |
| **Simple** | Run directly from the CLI — no MCP required |
| **Fast** | Rust-based binary |
| **Session management** | Manage multiple tabs in parallel with `--session` |

## Recommended Workflow

### 1. Pin down the reproduction conditions

- Document the target URL, user state (login/permissions/data), and expected vs. actual behavior.

### 2. Reproduce with agent-browser

```bash
# Open the page
agent-browser open https://example.com/target-page

# Capture an AI-optimized snapshot (interactive elements only)
agent-browser snapshot -i -c

# Example output:
# - button "Login" [ref=e1]
# - input "Email" [ref=e2]
# - input "Password" [ref=e3]
```

### 3. Execute actions to reproduce the issue

```bash
# Click by element reference
agent-browser click @e1

# Fill a form
agent-browser fill @e2 "test@example.com"
agent-browser fill @e3 "password123"

# Check state
agent-browser snapshot -i -c
```

### 4. Observe → hypothesize → inspect source

- Use snapshot, screenshot, and console log information to narrow down candidate root causes.
- Inspect relevant sources (UI, state management, API, validation).

### 5. Fix with the minimal change

- Keep the scope of changes small; be able to explain the intent and any side effects.

### 6. Re-verify with agent-browser

```bash
# Confirm the issue no longer reproduces with the same steps
agent-browser open https://example.com/target-page
agent-browser snapshot -i -c
agent-browser click @e1
# ...
```

## Fallback When agent-browser Is Unavailable

Try the following alternatives in order:

1. **MCP browser tools** (chrome-devtools, playwright)
2. **Manual reproduction**:
   - Reproduction steps (URL / actions / expected / actual)
   - Screenshots or video
   - Console logs / network logs
3. **Automated E2E**:
   - If feasible, add a minimal Playwright/Cypress test to prevent regressions.

## Common Commands

```bash
# Basic operations
agent-browser open <url>          # Open a page
agent-browser snapshot -i -c      # Snapshot (AI-optimized)
agent-browser click @e1           # Click
agent-browser fill @e2 "text"     # Fill input
agent-browser screenshot out.png  # Take a screenshot

# Debugging
agent-browser --headed open <url> # Show the browser window
agent-browser console             # Display console logs
agent-browser errors              # Display page errors

# Information retrieval
agent-browser get text @e1        # Get text
agent-browser get html @e1        # Get HTML
agent-browser get url             # Get current URL
```
